“Father, if thou be willing, remove this cup from me. Nevertheless, not my will but thine be done.'"

I find comfort in Jesus' most trying moment, as he's preparing to give his life for us, he's saying, “I don't want to have to do this. Is there another way? Can you remove this? Can you stop this?”

The greatest to ever walk this Earth, even He felt those feelings.

So when we are going through struggles and pain, we often say, “I don't want to suffer this, I don’t want to experience this, please take this from me.”

But we can find comfort in His words as He finishes his prayer off with “not my will but thine be done” 

That is Jesus from the beginning, from the premortal life. 

“Father thy will be done and the glory be thine forever.” 

All the way up to the end of his life, that phrase, “thy will be done” seems to be the phrase that defines him. 

He was willing to do the will of the Father from the beginning to the end. 

I think that might be the greatest definition of being Christlike. Learning how to submit to the will of the Father in our own personal bitter cups.

Because He conquered death and sin, there is hope for us. I know this is true. 

Happy Easter from my family 💜 #dalpias
